One America, Two Peoples
New York – As I write this, officials across the United States are still counting votes for the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
Once the final tally is determined, recounts and legal challenges will surely follow.
This is to be expected in an intensely competitive election with record-high voter turnout.
Only American citizens can vote for the president, but this choice affects people all over the country.
If it is too early to determine the election results now, it is not too early to explore what this election may mean for the world's most powerful nation.
On the positive side, the United States remains a strong democratic country.
Despite actual restrictions related to the pandemic, voter turnout was still high.
The process seems to be proceeding as planned.
And violent incidents are few.
Courts are investigating decisions by the US Postal Service department that seem to be politically motivated and are hindering the delivery of ballots from areas where voters are expected to be predominantly Democratic.
US President Donald Trump declared victory on Tuesday evening without any basis, and his calls to stop counting votes (at least in the states where he was leading) appear to have been ignored.
However, what is concerning is that there is still a significant divide among American voters.
The vote counts for the two candidates are nearly equal.
It is not surprising that this division could lead to a divided government.
If this trend continues, the Democrats will win the White House and retain control of the House of Representatives, while the Republicans will continue to control the Senate.
The governorships and state legislative seats were almost evenly split between the two parties (with a slight advantage for the Republicans).
The Democrats' expected "blue wave" did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a wide margin, securing several million more votes out of nearly 160 million cast.
But the Republicans held onto several Senate seats that many had predicted would flip, while the Democrats actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This result does not come from tough authorization or political adjustments.
Trump's polling numbers are excellent, with over five million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getter in American presidential election history, and surpassing any previous winner.
Especially noteworthy is that this happened against the backdrop of record-high daily新增病例和1000多例死亡病例。
Just as his government's handling of the pandemic became most severe, nearly half of voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems likely, he will still have strong influence, especially if he continues to remain in the public eye (which also seems likely).
Even if he does not run himself, he is likely to have a significant influence on the Republican nominee in the 2024 presidential election.
The Republican Party will be very different from the parties of Presidents Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism – modern American populism – will still be a powerful force.
Surprisingly, despite lacking any evidence, Trump is trying to present himself as morally upright, attempting to delegitimize the election results and accusing them of fraud.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept Biden's legitimacy as president.
Trump is very likely never to concede and will not attend the inauguration of his successor.
In Will Rogers' words, Trump has yet to encounter a norm he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They sort themselves into communities and regions based on similar viewpoints.
And each world tends to watch its own cable TV channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
And the lack of a national citizenship course facilitates the differentiation among people of different generations.
It is worth noting that, in most cases, the nation's differentiation is not along economic lines.
People from all strata voted for the two candidates, and the voting patterns based on population, gender, and race did not align as many predicted.
Their differences mainly lie in the corrective measures.
Education level is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geographical location. Republican voters tend to live in exurbs and rural areas, while Democrats prefer metropolitan areas.
However, the role of culture in American politics may be greater than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy does not seem to be very important in campaigns, except for mobilizing specific districts, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
Against this backdrop, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms to the presidential election process or the functioning of government.
This situation is no different from reforming the UN Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws, lack of representation, but no consensus can be reached on reform because any potential solution would benefit some while harming others.
It's not surprising that those who will lose out due to the changes will resist them.
This will make governance more difficult.
This will largely depend on Senate Republican leader Mitch McConnell's assessment, as well as his ability and willingness to cooperate with a future Biden presidency.
Collaboration will also require Biden to make compromises, which will certainly be met with resistance from more ideologically rigid members of his own party.
Democrats have tried to reject Trump and all of his representatives in a sharp way.
But they did not succeed.
The Republicans were seeking an election that would legitimize Trump.
And this too did not happen as they wished.
Instead, the election revealed a country and two kinds of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can do so remains to be seen.
